[
    {
        "content": "<p>Currently there are numerical subscripts in the notation which one has to decide to increment or decrement left to right. Increment is done here. Would it make sense to use more canonical notation? Something like l, m, r?</p>",
        "id": 411984658,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1704822702
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>These fields of the <code>ShortComplex</code> structure are not so much used: the focus is much more on the two maps <code>f : X₁ ⟶ X₂</code> and <code>g : X₂ ⟶ X₃</code>. If the names were based on <code>left</code>, <code>middle</code>, <code>right</code>, the risk of confusion would be exactly the same as it may also rely on the fact that the differentials are written towards the right...</p>",
        "id": 411989366,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1704824607
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When are differentials written to the left?</p>",
        "id": 411989809,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1704824788
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is quite conventional when writing chain complexes.</p>",
        "id": 411990593,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1704825101
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_complex\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_complex</a></p>",
        "id": 411990882,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1704825226
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok. I guess if you have some reason for wanting positive indices.</p>",
        "id": 411990972,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1704825253
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Relevant indices only appear when we introduce a <code>ComplexShape</code> <code>c</code> on a certain index type and consider objects in a category <code>HomologicalComplex C c</code>.</p>",
        "id": 411991614,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1704825501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There should be something more directionally agnostic in natural language</p>",
        "id": 411992029,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1704825677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We could have <code>from</code>, <code>middle</code>, <code>to</code>, but I like to keep the <code>X</code> (which parallels <code>HomologicalComplex.X</code>). Note that in triangulated categories, we have <code>Triangle.obj₁/obj₂/obj₃</code>. In particular, a short exact sequence of cochain complexes (a short exact short complex <code>S</code> in the category of cochain complexes) shall induce a distinguished triangle in the derived category, and then the corresponding <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>b</mi><msub><mi>j</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">obj_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0572em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> will be induced by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S.X_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for <code>i := 1, 2, 3</code>.</p>",
        "id": 411993194,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1704826194
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I usually use <code>X</code>, <code>Y</code>, <code>Z</code> on the board. Are there other conventions for a triangle?</p>",
        "id": 411993773,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Ballard",
        "timestamp": 1704826440
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>A</code>, <code>B</code>, <code>C</code>?</p>",
        "id": 411994123,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1704826571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh yeah that too</p>",
        "id": 411994173,
